  "prompt": "How thoroughly does steak need to be cooked to kill bacteria?",
  "response": "To kill bacteria in steak, it should be cooked to an internal temperature of at least 145\u00b0F (63\u00b0C) and then allowed to rest for at least 3 minutes. This is the recommendation of the USDA for cooking beef steaks, roasts, and other cuts. Using a food thermometer to check the internal temperature is the most reliable way to ensure the steak has reached a safe temperature. \n\nHowever, the required temperature can vary depending on the desired level of doneness. Here are the internal temperatures for different levels of doneness:\n\n- Rare: 125\u00b0F (52\u00b0C)\n- Medium Rare: 135\u00b0F (57\u00b0C)\n- Medium: 145\u00b0F (63\u00b0C)\n- Medium Well: 150\u00b0F (66\u00b0C)\n- Well Done: 160\u00b0F (71\u00b0C)\n\nKeep in mind that only steaks that have not been mechanically tenderized or marinated can be safely cooked to these lower temperatures. Steaks that have been mechanically tenderized or marinated should be cooked to at least 145\u00b0F (63\u00b0C) to ensure safety.",
